BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ted-posca-global-artist-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: TED & POSCA Global Artist Residency 2026: Visible Mending
DESCRIPTION:TED (the global platform for ideas and storytelling) and POSCA 
 (a creative brand by uni Brands Corporation) are launching a new kind of a
 rtist residency: a globally distributed cohort of artists working across d
 ifferent geographies\, cultures\, and communities\, united by a shared dri
 ve to shape public life through art. Fine Acts\, the external curatorial p
 artner selected by TED & POSCA\, leads the curation\, creative direction\,
  and coordination. There is no single location and no central studio: sele
 cted artists work within their own communities\, following a shared creati
 ve constraint (a unifying conceptual framework around repair\, hope\, and 
 beauty)\, with projects unfolding in public space\, community participatio
 n as a key part of the work\, and process mattering as much as outcome. 20
 26 THEME\, VISIBLE MENDING: inspired in part by Kintsugi (the Japanese pra
 ctice of repairing broken ceramics with gold)\, the theme explores repair 
 as a creative and civic act\, inviting artists to consider how wounds\, ru
 ptures\, and imperfections can become sites of transformation\, and to mak
 e processes of repair visible through public interventions that spark refl
 ection\, dialogue\, and collective imagination. In 2026\, four artists wil
 l be selected to develop community-rooted public interventions to be imple
 mented in 2027. AWARD: each selected artist receives a total of USD 15\,00
 0 to cover artist fees\, production costs/community activation\, and docum
 entation\, plus a production budget and tools from POSCA\, creative direct
 ion and storytelling support\, and visibility through TED and Fine Acts' g
 lobal platforms. While the residency term is one year\, the initiative wil
 l run for multiple years (2027\, 2028\, 2029)\, expanding the cohort year 
 by year and building an evolving global archive of civic artistic interven
 tions. Apply by 31 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: TED & POSCA (curated by Fin
 e Acts)\nLocation: Globally distributed\; no single location or central st
 udio. Selected artists work within their own communities\, with projects u
 nfolding in public space.\nAward: Each selected artist receives a total of
  USD 15\,000 (covering artist fees\, production costs/community activation
 \, and documentation)\, plus a production budget and tools from POSCA\, cr
 eative direction and storytelling support\, and visibility through TED and
  Fine Acts' global platforms.\nDuration: One-year residency term\; communi
 ty-rooted public interventions developed in 2026 for implementation in 202
 7. The initiative runs for multiple years (2027\, 2028\, 2029)\, expanding
  the cohort year by year.\n\nMore: https://fineacts.co/ted-posca-residency
URL:https://fineacts.co/ted-posca-residency
LOCATION:Globally distributed\; no single location or central studio. Selec
 ted artists work within their own communities\, with projects unfolding in
  public space.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rps-eamonn-mccabe-bursary-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260803
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260804
SUMMARY:Deadline: Eamonn McCabe Bursary 2026 (Royal Photographic Society)
DESCRIPTION:The Eamonn McCabe Bursary\, launched in 2024\, commemorates the
  life of photojournalist Eamonn McCabe (1948-2022)\, who made his name as 
 a sports photographer before moving to wider editorial work\, mainly for T
 he Observer and The Guardian\, and who supported a generation of photograp
 hers from the 1980s to the 2020s. Run by the RPS in partnership with McCab
 e's family and The Guardian\, this international bursary continues that le
 gacy. AWARD: GBP 3\,000 to a photographer aged 30 years or under to delive
 r a photography project responding to the theme of 'sporting endeavour'\, 
 which can be interpreted as widely as the applicant wishes\, though the ge
 neral approach should be suitable for publication. The project should norm
 ally be new\, not previously exhibited or published. As well as profession
 al sports\, the call particularly encourages projects covering grassroots 
 and community activities (for example\, addressing issues such as mental h
 ealth or supporting displaced communities)\, and welcomes creative interpr
 etations of the theme. The completed project will be published by The Guar
 dian and the RPS. ELIGIBILITY: applicants must be aged 30 years or under o
 n the closing date. PROCESS: interviews via Zoom in September\; recipient 
 announced by the end of September\; project completed within one year of a
 ward. Apply via the RPS application portal using RPS Account credentials. 
 Closing date 3 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: The Royal Photographic Societ
 y (RPS)\, in partnership with Eamonn McCabe's family and The Guardian\nLoc
 ation: International bursary. Applicants must be aged 30 years or under on
  the closing date. Interviews held via Zoom.\nAward: GBP 3\,000 to deliver
  a photography project on the theme of 'sporting endeavour'. The completed
  project will be published by The Guardian and the RPS\, who will work wit
 h the recipient to bring the project to a wider audience.\nDuration: The p
 roject should be completed within one year of being awarded.\n\nMore: http
 s://rps.org/opportunities/bursaries/eamonn-mccabe-bursary/
URL:https://rps.org/opportunities/bursaries/eamonn-mccabe-bursary/
LOCATION:International bursary. Applicants must be aged 30 years or under o
 n the closing date. Interviews held via Zoom.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:textile-exchange-atmos-fashion-regenerated-2026@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260720
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260721
SUMMARY:Deadline: Textile Exchange x Atmos: Fashion Regenerated 2026
DESCRIPTION:Fashion Regenerated is an open call from Textile Exchange and A
 tmos. Winners are selected by a panel of expert judges and\, for the first
  time\, a public vote. The shortlist is promoted through Textile Exchange 
 and Atmos\, amplifying inspirational stories to an engaged audience of tho
 usands. The overall winner receives a paid collaborative commission to the
  value of USD 10\,000 with Textile Exchange to develop a new body of work 
 documenting the evidence of regeneration\, working closely with the team t
 o identify the right story and access\; the winning work is published thro
 ugh Atmos\, Textile Exchange\, and shown to an audience of more than 1\,30
 0 changemakers at the 2026 Textile Exchange conference. Two runners-up hav
 e their work promoted by Textile Exchange and displayed at the conference 
 exhibition\, and there is also a USD 2\,000 cash prize. Check the call sit
 e for full eligibility and submission details. Deadline: 20 July 2026.\n\n
 Organisation: Textile Exchange (with Atmos)\nLocation: Open call\; work to
  be promoted globally through Textile Exchange and Atmos and exhibited at 
 the 2026 Textile Exchange conference.\nAward: Overall winner: a paid colla
 borative commission worth USD 10\,000 with Textile Exchange to develop a n
 ew body of work documenting the evidence of regeneration\, published throu
 gh Atmos and Textile Exchange and shown at the 2026 conference. Two runner
 s-up: work promoted by Textile Exchange and displayed at the conference ex
 hibition\, plus a USD 2\,000 cash prize.\nDuration: One-off commission/pri
 ze.\n\nMore: https://site.picter.com/fashion-regenerated-2026
URL:https://site.picter.com/fashion-regenerated-2026
LOCATION:Open call\; work to be promoted globally through Textile Exchange 
 and Atmos and exhibited at the 2026 Textile Exchange conference.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:artivism-amplifiers-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260701
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: Artivism & Amplifiers Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Artivism & Amplifiers (A&A) Fellowship pairs young climate 
 leaders from the Global North and Global South to co-create multimedia cam
 paigns\, exhibits\, and installations for the Creative Climate Awards 2027
 . Over six months\, fellows build skills in intercultural collaboration\, 
 climate storytelling\, and community engagement\, supported by expert work
 shops and creative mentors. The program is open to speakers of English\, S
 panish\, French\, and Portuguese. Fellows receive a USD 1\,000 stipend upo
 n completion. The organizers strongly encourage applications from people m
 ost impacted by the climate crisis\, including those from the global major
 ity\, Indigenous\, LGBTQIA+\, immigrant\, and diaspora communities\, and p
 eople with disabilities. Applications close Wednesday 1 July 2026 at 9am G
 MT+2.\n\nOrganisation: Human Impacts Institute\nLocation: Global\; pairs y
 oung climate leaders from the Global North and Global South. Open to speak
 ers of English\, Spanish\, French\, and Portuguese.\nAward: USD 1\,000 sti
 pend upon completion. Supported by expert workshops and creative mentors.\
 nDuration: Six-month program.\n\nMore: https://www.humanimpactsinstitute.o
 rg/opportunities
URL:https://www.humanimpactsinstitute.org/opportunities
LOCATION:Global\; pairs young climate leaders from the Global North and Glo
 bal South. Open to speakers of English\, Spanish\, French\, and Portuguese
 .
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:foundwork-artist-prize-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260925
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260926
SUMMARY:Deadline: Foundwork Artist Prize 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Foundwork Artist Prize is an annual juried award supporting
  outstanding artistic practices. The 2026 honoree receives an unrestricted
  USD 10\,000 grant\, studio visits with each of the five jurors\, and an i
 nterview for Foundwork's Dialogues program. In addition\, three artists ar
 e named to the 2026 Short List\, each receiving a USD 1\,000 micro-grant i
 n support of their practice. Submissions are made online through Foundwork
 . Application deadline 25 September 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Foundwork\nLoca
 tion: Open call. No location restriction stated\; submitted online via Fou
 ndwork.\nAward: The honoree receives an unrestricted USD 10\,000 grant\, s
 tudio visits with each of the five jurors\, and an interview for Foundwork
 's Dialogues program. Three artists named to the Short List each receive a
  USD 1\,000 micro-grant.\nDuration: One-off annual juried award.\n\nMore: 
 https://foundwork.art/artist-prize
URL:https://foundwork.art/artist-prize
LOCATION:Open call. No location restriction stated\; submitted online via F
 oundwork.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eidolon-grant-vernacular-photography-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260930
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261001
SUMMARY:Deadline: eidolon Grant 2026 (Vernacular Photography)
DESCRIPTION:The eidolon Grant is an international programme\, presented ann
 ually\, for projects that explore\, promote and conserve vernacular photog
 raphy. It is open to artists\, academics\, professionals\, researchers\, c
 ollectors and vernacular photography enthusiasts whose past work and propo
 sed project is centred around the image heritage of everyday photography. 
 The grant aims to identify phenomena\, collections\, histories\, practices
  and trends within vernacular photography\, offering new interpretations a
 nd analyses\, and thematising both photographic heritages and contemporary
  photographic practices. Applications can be made under two categories\, w
 ith a total of EUR 25\,000 to be distributed. Each chosen project will con
 tribute to the enrichment of eidolon's program in the coming year. The dea
 dline for submission is 30 September 2026 at 11:59 p.m. Apply via https://
 everydayphotography.org/centre/grant-2026.\n\nOrganisation: eidolon\nLocat
 ion: International\; open worldwide.\nAward: A total of EUR 25\,000 to be 
 distributed across two application categories. No application fee.\nDurati
 on: Annual grant\; supported projects contribute to the institution's prog
 ram in the coming year\n\nMore: https://everydayphotography.org/centre/gra
 nt-2026#about
URL:https://everydayphotography.org/centre/grant-2026#about
LOCATION:International\; open worldwide.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:async-museum-web-based-art-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261201
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261202
SUMMARY:Deadline: Async Museum: Open Call for Web-Based Art 2026
DESCRIPTION:Async Museum is an independent digital space dedicated to web a
 rt with a distinctive point of view\, existing to discover artists who use
  the web as their primary medium and to recognise their work as a new aest
 hetic. Its core philosophy is that the web browser is a twenty-first centu
 ry canvas. Async Museum is officially seeking submissions of web-based art
 works\, welcoming both established practitioners and emerging voices who a
 re pushing the boundaries of what the next generation of art can be. NOTE:
  this is an exhibition opportunity for web-based art rather than a paid gr
 ant\; no artist fee is stated. To share your practice and submit your work
 \, visit https://asyncmuseum.com/submit. Deadline: 1 December 2026.\n\nOrg
 anisation: Async Museum\nLocation: Online (independent digital space)\; op
 en to artists worldwide.\nAward: Exhibition and visibility opportunity\, N
 OT a paid grant: selected web-based artworks are presented in Async Museum
 's independent online space. No artist fee is stated.\nDuration: Rolling o
 pen call (exhibition in Async Museum's online space)\n\nMore: https://asyn
 cmuseum.com/submit
URL:https://asyncmuseum.com/submit
LOCATION:Online (independent digital space)\; open to artists worldwide.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:afac-music-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260701T070201Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260619
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260620
SUMMARY:Deadline: AFAC: Music Grant 2026 (Arab Fund for Arts and Culture)
DESCRIPTION:AFAC's Music grant supports music production\, performances\, c
 ollaborations\, album recordings\, music-related podcasts\, and festivals.
  The program provides annual grants of up to USD 25\,000 for individuals a
 nd teams\, and up to USD 35\,000 for collectives and institutions. WHO CAN
  APPLY: AFAC welcomes proposals from individuals from Arab countries (the 
 22 member states of the Arab League)\, regardless of place of residence\, 
 citizenship\, or ethnic and national identification\; it also accepts prop
 osals from local\, regional\, and international institutions and organizat
 ions (artistic and cultural institutions\, galleries\, venues\, and both n
 onprofit and for-profit entities) whose projects relate to arts and cultur
 e from the Arab region. INELIGIBLE: AFAC board\, staff\, their business pa
 rtners or family\, and current-year reader and juror committee members for
  the categories they evaluate\; recipients of grants in two consecutive ye
 ars are ineligible for the next two consecutive years\; and applicants wit
 h a current open grant. AFAC launches two open calls a year\; the second c
 all covers Cinema\, Music\, and Training & Regional Events grants. Each ap
 plicant may submit only one application per open call. WHAT IT COVERS: pro
 ject production including research and development\, covering project-rela
 ted expenses such as materials\, space or equipment rentals\, and fees for
  artistic and technical labor. An artist or institutional fee of up to 30%
  of the total grant is allowable. AFAC does not offer mobility grants\, th
 ough project-related travel may be covered\, and does not fund retroactive
 ly. PAYMENT: for grants above USD 10\,000\, applicants must show proof of 
 at least 50% of the remaining project budget secured\; payments are staged
  (50/35/15 for grants above USD 10\,000\, 70/30 for grants below). SELECTI
 ON: a grants management completeness review\, then an independent readers 
 committee\, then an independent jury committee that reaches the final deci
 sion. AFAC does not own any material or moral rights to supported projects
 . Applications are accepted only through the online forms (separate forms 
 for individuals\, teams\, collectives\, and institutions). TIMELINE: deadl
 ine 19 June 2026 at 5:00 PM +3 GMT (Beirut time)\; announcement of selecte
 d projects 16 November 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Arab Fund for Arts and Cultu
 re (AFAC)\nLocation: Arab region (open to individuals from the 22 Arab Lea
 gue states regardless of residence\; institutions local\, regional\, and i
 nternational working on Arab arts and culture)\nAward: Annual grants of up
  to USD 25\,000 for individuals and teams\, and up to USD 35\,000 for coll
 ectives and institutions. An artist or institutional fee of up to 30% of t
 he total grant is an allowable expense. No application fee.\nDuration: Pro
 jects to be completed within a maximum of two years from signature of the 
 grant agreement\n\nMore: https://www.arabculturefund.org/Programs/15
URL:https://www.arabculturefund.org/Programs/15
LOCATION:Arab region (open to individuals from the 22 Arab League states re
 gardless of residence\; institutions local\, regional\, and international 
 working on Arab arts and culture)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
